<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,1399,1745,2027]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<bibRefCitation author="Hayman" box="[189,495,1745,1772]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Hayman" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="1 - 105" refId="ref265860" refString="Hayman R. W., Misonne X. &amp; Verheyen W. N. 1966. The bats of the Congo and of Rwanda and Burundi. Annalen van het Koninklijk Museum voor Midden Afrika, Zoologische Wetenschappen, Ser. 8, 154: 1 - 105." type="journal article" year="1966">
Hayman 
<emphasis box="[298,360,1746,1772]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">et al.</emphasis>
(1966: 74)
</bibRefCitation>
reported a total of 
<specimenCount box="[733,909,1745,1772]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="generic">347 specimens</specimenCount>
from almost all over the 
<collectingCountry box="[1222,1286,1746,1772]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">DRC</collectingCountry>
. The 
<specimenCount pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="generic">560 specimens</specimenCount>
we found do not lead to a large extension of the range, but we do have some records from 
<collectingCountry box="[189,285,1818,1844]" name="Rwanda" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Rwanda</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[340,436,1818,1844]" name="Burundi" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Burundi</collectingCountry>
and from the southern part of Haut Kantanga Province. On the overall distribution, 
<bibRefCitation author="Thomas &amp; Henry" box="[189,488,1855,1881]" firstAuthor="Thomas" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="232 - 234" refId="ref273740" refString="Thomas D. &amp; Henry M. 2013 a. Eidolon helvum African Straw-coloured Fruit Bat. In: Happold M. &amp; Happold D. (eds) Mammals of Africa Volume IV. Hedgehogs, Shrews and Bats: 232 - 234. Bloomsbury Publishing, London." type="book chapter" year="2013" yearSuffix="a">Thomas &amp; Henry (2013a)</bibRefCitation>
show an almost uniform distribution south of the Sahara, with the exception of the drier areas of NE and SW Africa. Our assement of the distribution seems to suggest a split between a northern area and a southern/eastern area, which runs through the 
<collectingCountry box="[961,1021,1928,1954]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">DRC</collectingCountry>
provinces of Tanganyika, Haut- Lomami and Lualaba. Whether this is a real gap or only a result of the lack of voucher specimens cannot be determined at this time.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
